description.plain:
The Jonas Brothers are an American pop rock band. Formed in 2005, they have gained popularity from the Disney Channel children’s television network and consists of three brothers from Wyckoff, New Jersey: Kevin Jonas, Joe Jonas and Nick Jonas.

In the summer of 2008 they starred in the Disney Channel Original Movie Camp Rock and its sequel, Camp Rock 2: The Final Jam. They also starred as Kevin, Joe, and Nick Lucas in their own Disney Channel series JONAS, which was later re-branded for its second and last season as Jonas L.A.

In 2008, the group was nominated for the Best New Artist award at the 51st Grammy Awards and won the award for Breakthrough Artist at the American Music Awards. They have sold over eight million albums worldwide.

After a six year hiatus, Jonas Brothers reunited to release their comeback single, “Sucker” in March 2019. They later announced their album of return, Happiness Begins, in April 2019. On May 1st, 2019, they announced their first tour together in nearly a decade, “Happiness Begins Tour”.

songs.title: Sucker

description.plain:
“Sucker” is an upbeat pop song, and the band’s first single in almost six years. The brothers collectively portray someone who is infatuated with someone and for whom they would go to great lengths. The light rock instrumentation throughout the track is minimal, leaving the central focus on the brothers' vocals on their comeback single.

The song was teased in a YouTube video released by The Late Late Show with James Corden and was officially confirmed through a Twitter post:

https://twitter.com/jonasbrothers/status/1101133396200308736

songs.title: Cool

description.plain:
“Cool” is the second single and second track on the Jonas Brothers' fifth album, Happiness Begins. It was released in 2019, after the Jonas Brothers took a six-year hiatus. The lyrics contain numerous references to the brothers' personal and professional achievements during their years apart. Reflecting on their individual success, they describe a shared sense of satisfaction and peace of mind.

In the brothers' track descriptions for Apple Music, Nick explained:

This song came towards the end of the writing process. We were trying to write a ballad, actually, but we ended up writing this instead because we all came to the studio feeling very cool that day. Feeling like a million bucks.

The music video for the track has a strong eighties aesthetic.  According to a press release from the band, it’s meant to evoke “1984 Miami” and  “channel the spirit of timeless eighties MTV, in all its decadent glory.” The video features multiple references to previous Jonas Brothers projects, most notably the video for their 2008 hit, “Burnin' Up.”

The track was first introduced to social media via Instagram:

https://www.instagram.com/p/BvwXuKrHJPr/?utm_source=ig_embed
